ent participates in some international forums for energy with the apparent intent of becoming more sustainable, it is not able to implement any changes or plans due to the condition of the economy."},{"id":"clean-energy-investment","name":"Clean energy investment","value":"There are effectively no clean energy investments in Turkmenistan to date and the investment climate is not very conducive. Turkmenistan's policy of providing highly subsidized energy limits commercial viability of renewable projects. The Asian Development Bank had previously committed to investing heavily in Turkmenistan's power industry by funding potential projects. The status of these projects is unclear."},{"id":"power-prices-and-lcoes","name":"Power prices and LCOEs","value":"Subsidies for free, rationed electricity ended in 2018 and the government is attempting to force the installation of meters at every location. There are reports that the government is using police personnel to check for installations. Most citizens don't have the money to pay for meters or for electricity and may be jailed for not installing meters. The government is aiming to increase revenues, although it is unclear if the new policies have increased anything other than unrest."},{"id":"power-market","name":"Power market","value":"Natural gas is the main fuel for power generation in Turkmenistan. Power is controlled by the state, highly subsidized and also rationed. Blackouts and instability are common. Significant system upgrades are needed but the country does not have the resources for that."},{"id":"doing-business","name":"Doing business","value":"The country and its economy are effectively closed to the outside world. Independent offtake, contracts, and investments are extremely difficult, if not impossible, to secure. Any potential for the situation to improve is linked to global gas pricing and fundamentals."},{"id":"barriers","name":"Barriers","value":"Bureaucracy, and very slow processing of imports at the customs office, seriously inhibits trade."}]}
